           | Retry Behavior                     |\n   429â†’| ----------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------- |\n   430â†’| `'yes'`     | Subscriber is manually idempotent (safe to retry)                  | Retries allowed                    |\n   431â†’| `'no'`      | Subscriber is NOT idempotent (unsafe to retry)                     | Dead-letter on redelivery          |\n   432â†’| `'unknown'` | Idempotency not determined (default)                               | Retries allowed                    |\n   433â†’| `'resumable'` | Subscriber uses `io()` for checkpoint-based idempotency          | Retries allowed, checkpoint loaded |\n   434â†’\n   435â†’### `ResumableSubscriber`\n   436â†’\n   437â†’Matador supports durable / resumable subscribers.\n   438â†’\n   439â†’This allows subscribers that fail to resume where they left off, allowing you to retry subscribers that otherwise would not be idempotent.\n   440â†’\n   441â†’This requires a persistent `CheckpointStore` to be configured (e.g., Redis, database, etc.).\n   442â†’\n   443â†’When using `idempotent: 'resumable'`, you can use the `io` function argument to wrap side-effects, which will be cached when successful.\n   444â†’\n   445â†’On subsequent retries, those successful `io` calls will return the cached value, instead of executing again.\n   446â†’\n   447â†’```ts\n   448â†’import { MemoryCheckpointStore } from '@meetsmore/matador';\n   449â†’\n   450â†’// Configure Matador with a checkpoint store\n   451â†’const matador = new Matador({\n   452â†’  transport,\n   453â†’  topology,\n   454â†’  schema,\n   455â†’  consumeFrom: ['events'],\n   456â†’  checkpointStore: new MemoryCheckpointStore(), // Use RedisCheckpointStore in production\n   457â†’});\n   458â†’\n   459â†’// Define a resumable subscriber\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide an